{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"CI drift gate: every `external: true` volume declared in `infra/compose/docker-compose.yml` must be provisioned by `infra/scripts/compose-up.sh`, enforced in `make config-check` (already wired into test.yml AND gerrit-verify.yaml), so a compose-file edit that adds an external volume without a matching provisioning change can never reach `main`. Shift-left gate for incident 2731 (commit 10837ca88 added `gerrit_reviewbot_tickets: external: true` without updating compose-up.sh; every `compose up` then failed \"external volume not found\" for 41h).\n\n## Dependencies / rollout\nGated on bug e991-e347-3444-427c (compose-up.sh provisioning fix) landing FIRST (declared `depends_on` edge): until that fix lands, this check correctly reports the live drift and would fail CI on main. Rollout = land as a stacked Gerrit change directly on top of e991's commit; both changes pass the Verified gate on the stacked tree, and submit order (bottom-first) guarantees main is never in a state where the gate fails.\n\n## What (mechanism — single source of truth)\n- `infra/scripts/compose-up.sh`: hoist the currently-duplicated hardcoded subdir list into ONE top-level variable (`SITE_SUBDIRS=\"git index cache db etc logs plugins reviewbot reviewbot-tickets\"` — the 8 existing entries plus the missing one e991 adds), with volume-name derivation (`gerrit_` + subdir with `-` → `_`) in one shared helper function. The two provisioning loops AND the new `--print-volumes` mode all iterate that same variable through that same helper — there is no second copy of the list or of the derivation to drift.\n- `--print-volumes` mode: when `${1:-} == --print-volumes` (defaulted access — the script runs under `set -u`, so a bare `$1` would abort the normal zero-arg boot path), print the derived external volume names (one per line) and `exit 0`. The branch is placed immediately after the variable/helper definitions and BEFORE any side-effecting section (dnf/systemctl/docker/fetch-secrets), so it is side-effect-free by construction.\n- `infra/scripts/config-check.sh` check 5: extract `external: true` volume names from docker-compose.yml with `python3` + `yaml.safe_load` (the same interpreter+library dependency check 3 already uses — no grep/awk heuristics over multi-line YAML). Run `compose-up.sh --print-volumes` capturing output AND exit code; a non-zero exit or empty output is itself a FAIL (\"could not enumerate provisioned volumes\") — never treated as an empty provisioned set. Fail naming each missing volume and pointing at compose-up.sh as the fix site.\n- Self-test (pattern-regression guard) embedded in check 5: run the same extraction+comparison against an inline synthetic compose snippet declaring `gerrit_notprovisioned: external: true`; assert the check DETECTS it (non-zero, message contains the volume name and `compose-up.sh`). A silent false-negative regression of the extraction logic fails CI.\n- The `--print-volumes` contract is documented in both script headers (compose-up.sh: \"consumed by config-check.sh check 5\"; config-check.sh: \"requires compose-up.sh --print-volumes\").\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] AC1 (red / self-test): the embedded synthetic fixture with `gerrit_notprovisioned` makes the drift check exit non-zero with a message naming `gerrit_notprovisioned` and containing `compose-up.sh` — proven automatically on every `make config-check` run.\n- [ ] AC2 (green, in-session): `make config-check` exits 0 on this change's tree (stacked on e991, so `gerrit_reviewbot_tickets` is provisioned) — proven by running `make config-check` in the worktree before push and by the Verified vote on the stacked change.\n- [ ] AC3 (no side effects, deterministic): running `bash infra/scripts/compose-up.sh --print-volumes` with `PATH` pointing at stub `docker`/`dnf`/`systemctl` executables that each write a canary file prints the expected volume list (including `gerrit_reviewbot_tickets`), exits 0, and leaves NO canary file — proving no side-effecting binary was invoked. Proving command recorded in verify_commands.\n- [ ] AC4 (enumeration failure is loud, automated): check 5 embeds a second self-test that runs the same enumeration helper against a nonexistent script path and asserts it reports \"could not enumerate provisioned volumes\" (non-zero) rather than passing on an empty set — proven automatically on every `make config-check` run, same as AC1.\n\n\n## Alternative considered (and why rejected)\nParsing compose-up.sh's provisioning loop textually from config-check.sh (no new mode) was rejected: a grep/awk heuristic over bash silently drifts out of sync with the script's format (the same failure class this gate exists to prevent). `--print-volumes` executes the real list through the real derivation helper, so the check can only report what the script would actually do. Single consumer is acceptable: the mode is 4 lines and sits beside the data it exposes.\n- [ ] AC5 (contract documented): both script headers document the `--print-volumes` contract (compose-up.sh: \"consumed by config-check.sh check 5\"; config-check.sh: \"requires compose-up.sh --print-volumes\") — proven by grep in the change diff."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783685646671570001,"uuid":"ff60beec-d74f-4e5f-8c7b-fc81e52d3272"}